<br>

*Example 10*.

The previous example suggests a scale (~(a\/b), ~(a/\b)). Which of the following is a conversational implicature of the speaker having said that "It's not the case that Alex and Brianna attended"?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 Which one?
| The speaker believes that "Alex attended and Brianna attended"
| The speaker does not believe "It's not the case that Alex attended and Brianna attended"
| The speaker does not believe "Alex attended or Brianna attended"
| +The speaker does not believe "It's not the case that Alex attended or Brianna attended"
```

The **solution** is the last one, since this is the substitution instance of the entry ~(a\/b) to the left of the entry ~(a/\b).

