## Probability

This material pertains to the Week 9, Lecture 2 material. Please do not try this material until after that lecture.

<br>

*Example 11*

Complete the following truth-table, just like in Week 1.

~~~{.TruthTable .Simple system="gamutPND" options="nodash nocounterexample autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 p\/(q/\r)
~~~

The **solution** is just that it is true at the first five rows and false at the last three.

<br>

*Example 12*

This example builds off of the previous example. Suppose that each of the rows is weighted equally, that is each has equal chance of happening, namely a 1/8 chance of happening.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is the probability of p\/(q/\r) happening?
| 3/8
| 4/8
| +5/8
| 6/8
```

The **solution** is the third one, since 5/8 indicates that it is true at five of the eight rows.

<br>

*Example 13*

This example builds off of Example 11. Suppose that we assign the following probabilities to the rows in that truth-table:

| .1 -- TTT
| .1 -- TTF
| .1 -- TFT
| .2 -- TFF
| .3 -- FTT
| .05 -- FTF
| .05 -- FFT
| .1 -- FFF

<br>

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is the probability of p\/(q/\r) happening?
| .55
| .60
| .75
| +.80
```

The **solution** is the last one. The formula was true at the first five rows, and if you add up .1+.1+.1+.2+.3, you get .80.


<br>

*Example 14*

Suppose that you know that the probability of p is 25% and the probability of q is 25% and that the probability of p\/q is 40%. What is the probability of p/\q?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is the probability of p/\q?
| 5%
| 6.25%
| +10%
| 30%
```

The **solution** is 10%, which you get by doing 25%+25%-40%. This follows from the formula that Pr(p/\q)=Pr(p)+Pr(q)-Pr(p\/q).

<br>

*Example 15*

Suppose that you know that the probability of p is 25% and the probability of q is 25% and that the probability of p\/q is 40%. What is the probability of $\neg p \wedge \neg q$? *Hint*: use DeMorgan.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is the probability of ~p/\~q?
| 50%
| +60%
| 70%
| 80%
```

The **solution** is the second one, since by DeMorgan, $\neg p \wedge \neg q$ is equivalent to $\neg (p\vee q)$, and we can calculate that $Pr(\neg (p\vee q))=1-Pr(p\vee q) = 100-40 = 60$.

