## Conditional probability

This material pertains to the **Week 10**, Lecture 1 material. Please do not try this material until after that lecture.

<br>

*Example 16*

Complete the following truth-tables, just like in Week 1 and Week 3:


~~~{.TruthTable .Simple system="gamutPND" options="nodash nocounterexample autoAtoms" submission="none"}
 (~(p\/q)\/~r)/\r
~~~

The **solution** is that the formula (~(p\/q)\/~r)/\r is only true in the second to last row.

```{.TruthTable .Validity system="gamutPND" submission="none" options="nodash autoAtoms"}
 ~(p\/q)\/~r :|-: ~r\/~q
```

The **solution** is that the formula ~(p\/q)\/~r is true in the 2nd, 4th, and 6th, 7th, 8th rows. And ~r\/~q is only false in the 1st row and the 5th row. Hence, the argument is valid since there is no row where ~(p\/q)\/~r is true and ~r\/~q is false. (We will also produce a proof in Example 19 to show this validity).

<br>

*Example 17*

Suppose that each of the rows in the previous truth-tables are weighted equally, that is each has equal chance of happening, namely a 1/8 chance of happening. What is the probability of ~(p\/q)\/~r conditional on r?

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is the probability of ~(p\/q)\/~r conditional on r?
| 1/8
| +2/8
| 3/8
| 4/8
```

The **solution** is 2/8 since by the tables we have that the probability of (~(p\/q)\/~r)/\r is 1/8 and the probability of r is 1/2 (since r is true in four out of eight rows). Hence we have 1/8 divided by 1/2, which is the same as 1/8 times 2, which is 2/8.

<br>

*Example 19*

Show the following, using distribution:

```{.ProofChecker .GamutPNDPlus submission="none"}
  ~(p\/q)\/~r  :|-: ~r\/~q
|~(p\/q)\/~r :assumption
|(~p/\~q)\/~r :DMAND1
|~r\/(~p/\~q) :LCD2
|(~r\/~p)/\(~r\/~q) :LDD3
|(~r\/~q) :E/\4
```

<br>

*Example 20*

Suppose that each of the rows in the truth-table in Example 16 is weighted equally, that is each has equal chance of happening, namely a 1/8 chance of happening. Use Bayes's theorem, and the tables in Example 16, to calculate the probability of ~(p\/q)\/~r conditional on ~r\/~q.

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice submission="none" options="check"}
 What is the probability of ~(p\/q)\/~r conditional on ~r\/~q?
| +5/6
| 1/8
| 1/6
| 6/8
```

By Bayes' theorem and Example 19, the probability is just the probability of ~(p\/q)\/~r divided by the probability of ~r\/~q. By the tables, we know that the former is 5/8 and the latter is 6/8.

